1.1 Login to lakeshore

1.1.0.0.0.1 For Windows Users
  1. Open PuTTY
  2. Enter lakeshore.acer.uic.edu as HostName

  1. Click Open
  2. Enter your netID at the “login as:” prompt
1.1.0.0.0.2 For macOS/Linux Users
  1. Open Terminal appliation
  2. Execute the following
ssh <netID>@lakeshore.acer.uic.edu

1.1.1 Public Key Authentication

1.1.1.0.0.1 For Windows Users
  1. Enter login username in Connection->Data

  1. Click Browse in Connection->SSH->Auth and load your key.

1.3.2 Explore cd and pwd Commands

  • Change (current) directory; go to home directory.
cd
  • Print the working (current) directory
pwd
  • This will take you to the 2_LinuxHPC directory using absolute path.
cd /workshops/ric_workshop/common/2_LinuxHPC
pwd
  • This will take you one level above (i.e. to common)
cd ./../
pwd
  • This will take you two level above from our current directory
cd ./../../
pwd
  • Go back to the last working directory
cd -
pwd

1.4 Working with files and directories

1.4.1 Create, Rename, and Delete directory

  • Create a directory under your home directory
mkdir ~/workingdir
  • Create a sub directory called newdir
mkdir /home/<netid>/workingdir/newdir
  • Rename the directory called ‘newdir’ to ‘myfirstdir’
cd workingdir
mv newdir myfirstsubdir
rm myfirstsubdir
rm: cannot remove 'myfirstsubdir': Is a directory

Command will fail, as we need -r (recursive) for directories

rm -r myfirstsubdir

Remove directory called ‘myfirstdir’. This will remove all the subdirectories and files in ‘myfirstdir’.

1.4.2 Working with files: Create, copy, move, and delete a file

  • Go to workingdir directory
cd ~/workingdir
  • Create an empty file
touch myfirstfile.txt
  • Make a copy of file ‘myfirstfile.txt’ and name it 2.txt. Both the files are in the same directory.
cp myfirstfile.txt 2.txt
  • Move 2.txt file to my home directory and rename it to two.txt. Note:The mvcommand can also rename a file while moving it to a different location!
mv 2.txt ~/two.txt
  • List the directory to see the results
ls
myfirstfile.txt
myfirstsubdir
  • List your home directory
ls ~

1.6.2 Echo Command, Redirects and Pipes

  • Go to workingdir directory
cd ~/workingdir
  • 1> redirects STDOUT (stream 1) to a new file called ‘filename.txt’.
echo "Today's Workshop Day is all about linux" 1> filename.txt
  • >> appends to the same file
echo "We are learning about redirects" >> filename.txt
  • >> append again
echo "This exercise is about understanding redirects" >> filename.txt
  • ‘<’ reads file into STDIN
head -n 2 < filename.txt
Today's Workshop Day is all about linux
We are learning about redirects
cat filename.txt 1> t1.txt  ## (STDOUT)
wc -l t1.txt  ## count number lines in the t1.txt
3 t1.txt
  • If filename.txt does not exist, error message is on STDERR (stream 2)
cat filename.txt 2> output.txt
cat output.txt
Today's Workshop Day is all about linux
We are learning about redirects
This exercise is about understanding redirects
  • Let’s stich few commands together using ‘pipe’. Goal: Get top 10 lines from hg19_chr19.gtf, and then redirect last five line to temp.txt
head hg19_chr19.gtf | tail -n 5 > temp.txt

1.7 Filter utilities

Using cut, less/more, sort, and uniq commands to view the content of the gtf file

  • Go to workingdir directory
cd ~/workingdir
  • If you haven’t already done so, make a copy of the hg19_chr19.gtf file
cp /workshops/ric_workshop/common/2_LinuxHPC/hg19_chr19_annotation.gtf hg19_chr19.gtf
  • Cut column 1 and 3 from hg19_chr19.gtf
cut -f 1,3 hg19_chr19.gtf
##description: evidence-based annotation of the human genome (GRCh37), version 19 (Ensembl 74)
##provider: GENCODE
##contact: gencode@sanger.ac.uk
##format: gtf
chr19   gene
chr19   transcript
chr19   exon
chr19   exon
chr19   exon
chr19   exon
  • Cut column 1 and 3 from hg19_chr19.gtf, pipe to less to view page at a time
cut -f 1,3 hg19_chr19.gtf | less
  • Cut column 3 from hg19_chr19.gtf, pipe to sort, pipe to uniq command to count number of uniq feature records and associated counts and sort again.
cut -f 3 hg19_chr19.gtf | sort | uniq -c
  44556 CDS
      1 ##contact: gencode@sanger.ac.uk
      1 ##description: evidence-based annotation of the human genome (GRCh37), version 19 (Ensembl 74)
  72639 exon
      1 ##format: gtf

     16 Selenocysteine
   6375 start_codon
   5710 stop_codon
cut -f 3 hg19_chr19.gtf | sort | uniq -c | sort -g

2.4.2 while loop (Take home Exercise)

  • Go to workingdir directory

  • Edit a new file named gene_names.txt

  • Edit the file to have the following contents
APOE
NOTCH3
ERCC1

  • Save the file (Ctrl + O) and quit (Ctrl + X).

  • Edit a new file named whileloop.sh

nano whileloop.sh
  • Edit the file to have the following contents
#!/bin/sh
file_list=$1    # First argument: file containing list of search terms (e.g., gene names)
file_data=$2    # Second argument: file where we want to search those terms
file_out-=$3    # Third argument: file where we will save output
# Loop through each line in the list file
while read -r line; do
    echo "Searching for: $line" 
    # Search for exact match of $line in the input file
    # within that search keep only lines which word gene
    # append results to output file
    grep -w $line $file_data | grep -w gene >> $file_out
  done < "$file_list"

  • Save the file (Ctrl + O) and quit (Ctrl + X).

  • Execute the script

sh whileloop.sh gene_names.txt hg19_chr19.gtf subset_chr19.gtf

3.2.2 Print gene IDs where any expression value > 7.5

  • Loop through all expression columns. If any sample has a value > 7.5,
    print the gene ID. Observation
    • NR > 1 skip the header row
    • i=2 correctly skips the Ensemble ID (1st column) and checks only sample columns
    • NF = number of fields (Ensemble ID column + all sample columns)
    • break stops after first match
awk 'NR > 1 { \
  for(i=2;i<=NF;i++) \
    if($i > 7.5) { print $1; break } \
}' GSE160351_DESEQ2_normalized_counts.txt
ENSG00000227232
ENSG00000268903
ENSG00000269981
ENSG00000241860
ENSG00000279457
ENSG00000237094
ENSG00000225630
ENSG00000237973
ENSG00000248527
ENSG00000198744

3.2.3 Replace Sample Prefixes in Header (Lib_ → Sample_)

  • Observation:
    • 1: Only apply to line 1 (the header row).
    • s: Substitute (search and replace).
    • Lib_: The pattern to find (sample names start with this).
    • Sample_: The replacement text.
    • g: Global, meaning replace all occurrences on that line (not just the first one).
sed '1s/Lib_/Sample_/g' GSE160351_DESEQ2_normalized_counts.txt
